    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>If Tohma Faulkner [a member of the Brownstoners of Bedford-Stuyvesant, a local group dedicated to preserving old housing] is so concerned about the escalating prices in Bedford-Stuyvesant [''Discovering Bed-Stuy's Brownstones,'' May 21], she should buy all the for-sale buildings at the full asking price, then resell them to young people and her goddaughter at rock-bottom prices so that her ''community of extended family will not be priced out.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>If Tohma Faulkner [a member of the Brownstoners of Bedford-Stuyvesant, a local group dedicated to preserving old housing] is so concerned about the escalating prices in Bedford-Stuyvesant [''Discovering Bed-Stuy's Brownstones,'' May 21], she should buy all the for-sale buildings at the full asking price, then resell them to young people and her goddaughter at rock-bottom prices so that her ''community of extended family will not be priced out.''</p>
        <p>I doubt if the sellers are so altruistic. In the world of real estate it is the love of money that drives the engine.</p>
        <p>SID MILLER  Director, the Haven Heights Group  Real Estate Brokers  Bronx</p>
      </block>
